TPComments: Some of the questions were ambiguous. I am an owner of an AV and work for an auto manufacturer who produces autonomous vehicles. However I wasn’t sure if I should answer the questions in a way of what do I currently have or what would I desire. I answered with my desires in mind.

From the questions provided, there is weight on the social connectivity of these devices and the concept of immersion. While these can be beneficial attributes, their ability to draw away from the functionality is my main concern. I think distraction and loosing track of time are detrimental to human factors and the interaction of the user and the interface to accomplish a goal. The main case where this would be mitigated would be in a fully autonomous vehicle where the user's attention have no impact on the accomplishment of the desire goal (transport). In this case, it would be a great advantage to have this capability.

I personally find drivers attention to the road to be the biggest concerning factor in America, which is why I raised this point. Furthermore the wandering gaze to screens and connective devices whether they be installed in the car or handheld are a primary issue for the distracted drivers, typically manifested through social media our audio/video immersion. For elevation of human factors in automobiles, car autonomy and heads up displays are primary to the improvement in performance and safety. Additionally, voice activated control over secondary functionality (social, immersion, etc) would be of great benefit as the world is moving toward hands free but are still limited in functionality due to voice recognition capabilities in current devices.
The question regarding “moderation:” in the beginning was unclear and thus the answer there less reliable.
The survey was interesting and informative.
Overall, reliability and easy to use are the most important factors for me.  A simple and straightforward user interface without needing to dig out the thick menu is a must.
